  "issue_title": "M1 exit: memory recall test set (\u2265 20 cases) passes \u2265 95%",
  "issue_body": "## Goal\n\nProve household memory recall works reliably and **recall failures are\nobservable, not silent**.\n\n## What to build\n\n- A curated test set of **\u2265 20 memory recall cases** covering shared-room\n  scope, sensitivity levels, and `spoken_policy` filtering \u2014 e.g.,\n  \"remember X\" \u2192 next session \u2192 \"what did you remember about X?\"\n- A test runner that seeds memory, restarts the stack, asks the recall\n  question, and scores hit/miss against expected content\n- Failure path: when recall misses, a structured log entry must fire\n  (not a silent empty context)\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] \u2265 20 cases curated and committed under `tests/memory/`\n- [ ] Test set passes \u2265 95% on a clean stack\n- [ ] Recall miss emits a labeled log line distinguishable from a hit\n- [ ] Promoted-durable filtering (`memory/MEMORY.md`) verified \u2014 shared-safe entries only\n\n## Context\n\nTracks one of the five M1 exit criteria from the README roadmap. See\n[`Roadmap` in README.md](../blob/main/README.md#roadmap) and the\n\"Memory Safety Notes\" section.",
